introduction.p:
The whole chapter can be read as one sentence:

  \boxed{
  \int_{\partial M}\omega=\int_M d\omega.
  }

The rest is translation.

p.md:
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
\dim M \amp M \amp \partial M \amp \omega \\ \hline
1 \amp \text{interval} \amp \text{signed endpoints} \amp 0\text{-form}\\[1mm]
2 \amp \text{plane region} \amp \text{oriented boundary curve} \amp 1\text{-form}\\[1mm]
2 \amp \text{surface in space} \amp \text{oriented boundary curve} \amp 1\text{-form}\\[1mm]
3 \amp \text{solid region} \amp \text{outward-oriented boundary surface} \amp 2\text{-form}
\end{array}

subsection.p:
For a plane 1-form,

  \omega=P\,dx+Q\,dy,


  \boxed{
  d\omega=(Q_x-P_y)\,dx\wedge dy.
  }

For a flux 2-form,

  \Phi=P\,dy\wedge dz+Q\,dz\wedge dx+R\,dx\wedge dy,


  \boxed{
  d\Phi=(P_x+Q_y+R_z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.
  }

This is the divergence volume form.

The orientation rules are just as important:

  \begin{array}{c|c}
  \text{Object} \amp \text{Induced boundary orientation} \\ \hline
  [a,b] \amp \partial[a,b]=\{b\}-\{a\}\\[1mm]
  \text{plane region} \amp \text{walk so the region stays on the left}\\[1mm]
  \text{oriented surface} \amp \text{right-hand rule}\\[1mm]
  \text{solid region} \amp \text{outward-oriented boundary surface}
  \end{array}

introduction.p:
For each row below, fill in the missing details.

  \begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
  \text{Name} \amp M \amp \omega \amp d\omega \\ \hline
  \text{Fundamental Theorem of Calculus}
  \amp [a,b]
  \amp f
  \amp df
  \\[1mm]
  \text{Green's theorem}
  \amp R\subset\mathbb R^2
  \amp P\,dx+Q\,dy
  \amp (Q_x-P_y)\,dx\wedge dy
  \\[1mm]
  \text{Classical Stokes' theorem}
  \amp S\subset\mathbb R^3
  \amp P\,dx+Q\,dy+R\,dz
  \amp \Phi_{\nabla\times\mathbf F}
  \\[1mm]
  \text{Divergence theorem}
  \amp E\subset\mathbb R^3
  \amp \Phi_{\mathbf F}
  \amp (\nabla\cdot\mathbf F)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz
  \end{array}

subsection.p:
So the balance law becomes

  \boxed{
  \frac{d}{dt}
  \int_E \rho\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz
  =
  -
  \int_{\partial E}\Phi_{\mathbf J}.
  }

Using Stokes' theorem,

  \boxed{
  \frac{d}{dt}
  \int_E \rho\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz
  =
  -
  \int_E d\Phi_{\mathbf J}.
  }

